👉 What is Inheritance?

Inheritance is used t borrow properties and methods from an existing class.
+-------------+-------------+
| Phone       | Smart Phone |
| Super class | Sub class   |
+-------------+-------------+

Declaring Inheritance in Java
Inheritance in JAVA is declared using extends keyword

+-------------+
| Superclass  |
+-------------+
      ⬇️
+-------------+
| Subclass    |     --> Here subclass extends the superclass / subclass is derived from superclass
+-------------+

MORE REAL WORLD EXAMPLES : 

+---------+--------+--------+---------+
| Vehicle | Animal | Animal | Vehicle |
+---------+--------+--------+---------+
| Car     | Dog    | Cat    | Truck   |
+---------+--------+--------+---------+

When a class inherits from a superclass , it inherits parts of superclass methods and fields. Java doesn't support multiple inheritance
i.e. two classed can't be duperclass for a subclass

For example : 

class Base{
    int x;
    public void print(){
        System.out.println("This is base class");
    }

    public int getX() {
        return x;
    }

    public void setX(int x) {
        this.x = x;
    }
}
class Derived extends Base{            // extends Base → This means Derived inherits all fields and methods from Base.
    int y;

    public int getY() {
        return y;
    }

    public void setY(int y) {
        this.y = y;
    }
}
public class Inheritance {
    public static void main(String[] args){
        Base b = new Base();
        b.setX(4);
        System.out.println("Base class : "+b.getX());
        Derived d = new Derived();
        d.setY(5);
        System.out.println("Dervied class Setting Y : "+d.getY());
        d.setX(6);
        System.out.println("Derived class setting X : "+d.getX());
    }
}

👉 Derived has:

1. Its own variable y with getter/setter.
2. Access to x, getX(), setX(), and print() from Base.

Key Point : Inheritance allows code reuse — Derived doesn’t need to rewrite x or its methods.


